      <h2 id="best-budget">Best Budget: Amazon Basics Plastic Footrest</h2>
      <p>If you want to spend under $15 and do not need height adjustability, the Amazon Basics plastic footrest is the value pick. It offers a single fixed height of about 4.5 inches with a curved rocking design that lets you tilt your feet forward and back, which provides some of the circulation benefit of an adjustable rest. The textured surface is more aggressive than the HUANUO's, which some users prefer for stimulation and others find irritating in thin socks.</p>
      <p>The tradeoffs are real. There is no height adjustment, so if 4.5 inches is wrong for your chair height, you are out of luck. There is no cushioning, so the hard plastic can fatigue your feet over a full day — most users end up putting a folded towel on top. The base slides more readily than the HUANUO on hard floors. For a secondary desk, a guest station, or a short daily use case, it works. For eight-hour daily use, the HUANUO's adjustability and cushion are worth the extra $13.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying Guide</h2>
      <p>The first decision is whether you need adjustability. If you are the only user and your chair height is fixed, you can measure the gap between your feet and the floor at correct desk height and buy a fixed rest that matches. If multiple people use the desk, or you alternate between sitting and standing, an adjustable rest is worth the premium. Measure the gap with your chair at the height where your elbows are at desk level — that is the height your footrest needs to fill.</p>
      <p>Tilt is the underrated feature. A flat footrest is better than nothing, but a tilting rest lets you rock your feet throughout the day, which is what actually improves circulation. Static foot positioning, even on a cushion, causes the same pooling problems as no footrest at all. Look for a rest with at least 15 degrees of tilt in both directions, and verify that the tilt mechanism is rated to hold your foot weight without collapsing. The HUANUO's 30-degree range is generous and designed for stable use across a range of user weights.</p>
      <p>Finally, consider the surface and base together. A textured or cushioned top improves comfort and circulation; a smooth plastic top gets slippery and fatiguing. For the base, rubber or textured non-slip material is essential on hard floors — smooth plastic bases slide forward every time you shift your feet, and you will spend the day repositioning the rest. If you have carpet, any base works, but check that the rest is wide enough that it does not tip when you lean to one side. A rest that tips when you shift weight is worse than no rest at all.</p>
      <p>Learn more about our <a href="/how-we-test/">evaluation methodology</a> and <a href="/editorial-policy/">editorial policy</a>.</p>

      <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        <details>
          <summary>Does a foot rest actually help with back pain?</summary>
          <p>Yes, when paired with proper chair height. A footrest relieves pressure on the lower back by raising the knees slightly and improving pelvic alignment. It is most effective for shorter users whose feet do not flat-touch the floor at correct desk height, and for anyone who sits more than 4 hours a day.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>What height should a foot rest be set to?</summary>
          <p>Start with your feet flat on the floor and your knees at roughly 90 degrees. If your chair is too high to achieve that, raise the footrest until your thighs are parallel to the floor. Most people land between 4 and 6 inches. Tilt should be set so your ankles feel neutral, not stretched.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Are textured massage foot rests comfortable for all-day use?</summary>
          <p>For short stretches, yes. The textured bumps stimulate circulation when you rock your feet. For all-day wear with thin-soled shoes or socks, the texture can become irritating. Look for a rest with a removable cushioned cover, or wear shoes if you use the textured side continuously.</p>
        </details>
      </div>

